That’s a fancy way of saying the government should buy out property owners in flood-prone areas instead of repeatedly paying  insurance claims to rebuild. But it’s complicated. Recent research shows the current buyout regime varies widely by state, does not correlate with where the damage is occuring, and might even bring with it a racial disparity.

</div>

    <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-1'><p>Citing NOAA, a CNBC article states that “from 2016 to 2018, the average number of billion-dollar disasters totaled 15 each year, while the average for 1980–2018 was just 6.2 events per year.” A Federal Emergency Management Agency  official quoted in the story makes the case that “the need for forward-leaning action is greater than ever before."</p>    

</div>



    <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-2'><p>Given the urgency of climate change, it’s surprising at first to discover that the overall numbers of buyouts in the country are decreasing. That is, until you disaggregate the data by state — a classic case of Simpson’s paradox, where the national trend obscures interesting local analyses. In 1993, Missouri and Illinois alone took over 5,000 buyouts due to storms and flooding, contributing to the trend’s all time high of 8,000. But while the participation of the Midwest in the program has steadily dwindled by hundreds, the program has seen steady if small upticks in participation among states on the East Coast.</p> 
