    <div class="steps">
        <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-2'><p>It is tempting to look at the geographic distribution of buyouts and tell a tale of changing climate vulnerability in the United States; certainly this hypothesis plays out in the context of buyouts in New York, New Jersey and parts of New England, as there is a clear link between increasing numbers of buyouts and Superstorm Sandy. But a recent Science Advances study published in October raises concern about social equity in this context and suggests that buyouts don’t paint a simple picture of changing disaster zones. Rather, there are confounding variables that determine whether or not communities take buyouts, independent of the level of damage they might suffer — such as how white and wealthy they might be.</p></div>


        <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-3'><p>As a Houma Today editorial from October put it, “The top three states in total property damage are in the middle of the buyout pack. Florida had $98.8 billion in damage, Louisiana $85.4 billion and Mississippi $34.2 billion. Yet Florida is 24th in the number of homes purchased, Mississippi 22nd and Louisiana 19th, with a total of just over 2,000 buyouts in the three states.”</p></div>

        <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-3'><p>An NPR investigation from earlier this year found that buyouts disproportionately went to whiter and wealthier communities in the country. One reason for this might be that FEMA provides only 75 percent of the funding required to execute a buyout project. The findings of the October study complicate this picture slightly; researchers found that while the counties that participated in buyout programs tended to be wealthy, zipcodes in which buyouts where implemented were not necessarily so. This finding gives rise to concerns about urban displacement among vulnerable groups, and it wouldn’t be the first time; in post-Katrina New Orleans, the “green dot” redevelopment program caused great consternation among African American residents in the city.</p></div> 

        <div class="step" data-show-selector='#grid-step-4'><p>If it is indeed true that large-scale buyouts need to be part of the conversation about climate change, making sure that we completely understand the social implications of their implementation so far needs to be a priority.</p> </div>
